article.description: Maria Stepanova and Anna DeForge each scored 14 points to lead the Phoenix Mercury over Detroit 58-51 Tuesday night.
article.headline: Detroit's four-game win streak ends
article.linkText: Mercury move into fourth with win over Shock
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- Maria Stepanova and Anna DeForge each scored 14
points to lead the Phoenix Mercury over Detroit 58-51 Tuesday
night, snapping the Shock's four-game winning streak.

Despite getting outrebounded 38-28, the Mercury (14-14) remained
in sole possession of the fourth and final playoff spot in the
Western Conference.

Katie Smith scored 11 points and Cheryl Ford added 10 for the
Shock (14-15), who remained tied with Washington for fourth place
in the East.

Detroit made just 4 of 31 shots from the field in the second
half after leading by as many as 10 points in the first 20 minutes.

Penny Taylor added nine of her 11 points in the second half, and
Kamila Vodichkova also scored 11 for the Mercury, who have won 11
of 14.

Diana Taurasi, Phoenix's leading scorer, was held scoreless for
only the second time in her career and the first time this season.
She was 0-for-5 from the field and played in foul trouble much of
the night.

Stepanova added four rebounds and four blocked shots. The
Mercury announced before the game that Stepanova, who came into the
game averaging 10.6 points and a WNBA-leading 2.4 blocks, was
scheduled to leave the team on Wednesday to rejoin the Russian
national team.
